		<div id="comment_body_64587785"><p><div class="quote"><p>Another good countermeasure is to increase the value of live rhinos through tourism, trophy hunting, or whatever, creating jobs for locals.</p><p>That gives the local people an incentive to oppose the poachers, who are often their friends and neighbors.</p><p>This strategy has been a resounding success in South Africa and is now working in Kenya.</p></div><p>I'd add in taking people that want to hunt rhinos on these trips to tag the horns with radioactive tracers.  They won't have a lethal weapon but instead a tranquilizer dart gun.  They get the thrill of a hunt, a "trophy photo" with themselves and the knocked out rhino, and maybe they can take the small pieces of the horn home that were created in the drilling of the horn to put in the tracer.</p><p>There could certainly be lawful hunting of rhinos for the meat, horn, hide, or whatever.  Even if endangered there's<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64587785">

